"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-teen-track-star-quincy-wilson-qualify-paris-olympics-relay\", \"text\": \"He has yet to earn his driver\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s license, but 16-year-old track phenom Quincy Wilson has earned himself a chance to go to theParis Olympicsthis summer.\\u00c2  Competing against elite athletes nearly twice his age in theU.S. Olympic track and field trialsin Eugene, Ore., the high school sophomore broke the under-18 world record in the 400 meters\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094a mark that dated back 42 years\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094when he ran a 44.66 in the first round on Friday. Then on Sunday, he surpassed his own mark with a 44.59 finish to advance to Monday\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s final.\\u00c2  In front of an energized crowd at Hayward Field on Monday night, Wilson, donning his singlet from Bullis High School in Potomac, Maryland, finished sixth in the final with a time of 44.94 seconds, denying him an automatic bid to Paris. Winner Quincy Hall finished in a personal-best 44.17 seconds to qualify, followed by Michael Norman (44.41) and Chris Bailey (44.42).  Quincy Hall DIGS DEEP down the homestretch to win the Olympic Trials 400m final in the fastest time by an American this year!#TrackFieldTrials24pic.twitter.com/iaeLxrH7Lp  While those three will represent the U.S. in the 400 in Paris in less than a month, Wilson\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s opportunity to join Team USA at the Summer Games is not lost. He could still become a 2024 Olympian if he is selected for the U.S. relay pool, a decision made by the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s relay coach Mike Marsh and a USA Track & Field selection panel after trials are complete. In addition to the three men who qualified for the individual 400-meter event, the U.S. can bring four more runners: two for the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 4x400-meter relay and two for the mixed relay. For Tokyo, for example, the top seven finishers in the 400-meter final at U.S. trials were all selected as part of the relay pool.\\u00c2  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI can\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t be disappointed,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009dWilson said after Monday\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s final. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAt the end of the day, I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m 16 years old running\\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6grown-man times.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d\\u00c2  If selected for the relay pool, Wilson will become the youngest American male to make the Olympic track and field team, and the first 16-year-old since Sydney McLaughlin-Levrone qualified for the Rio Games in 2016. Any preparation for that driver\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s license will also have to wait.\\u00c2  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s spectacular,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d said Tokyo 4x400 relay gold medalist Norman, after the semifinal race. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cA 16-year-old coming out here, competing like a true competitor, not letting the moment get too big but living in the moment.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Jamie Lisanti is an assistant managing editor at Sports Illustrated. A former college soccer player, she covers a variety of topics, including tennis, Olympics, fitness and nutrition, and more.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"